Description

UNOCS is a safety ontology designed to unify construction safety knowledge from diverse sources, enabling automated reasoning, safety rule checking, and improved hazard identification. By integrating data from BIM, IoT, and virtual training, it supports informed decision-making and enhances interoperability among stakeholders.

Overview

UNOCS and alignment to other ontologies

A holistic safety ontology requires a broad knowledge base and specific domain expertise. Using ontology modularization, UNOCS reduces complexity by dividing the ontology into reusable, purpose-driven modules. This approach enables flexible extensions and simplifies development and maintenance. Organization UNOCS reuses DiCon and OCQA as modules to provide the basic terminologies and concepts related to construction execution and inspection planning, respectively. DiCon is a higher-level domain ontology that generalizes construction workflow knowledge with related entities and properties . The DiCon ontology contains basic concepts for describing components related to construction processes. DiCon aligns with existing relevant ontologies that enable the direct integration of heterogeneous systems in the construction domain like ifcOWL and BOT to integrate building information models, organizational descriptions, and schedules. The OCQA is a formal and comprehensive knowledge representation and terminology for representing and planning inspection plans in construction. The descriptions are relevant due to one of the specified use cases in order to inspect safety equipment on site. In addition, the ontology enables the collection of inspection-related data from heterogeneous sources, which improves interoperability and enables networked and project-related planning between project participants.

Figure 1: Overview of Core UNOCS module.

Core of UNOCS

The Core Ontology Module of UNOCS establishes the fundamental entities and relationships necessary for managing construction safety knowledge. It connects hazards to incidents through the unocs:causes property, illustrating how hazards can lead to incidents, and models the involvement of victims using unocs:hasVictim. To mitigate these risks, hazards are linked to corrective actions (unocs:CorrectiveAction) that reduce the likelihood of incidents. Safety inspections (unocs:SafetyInspection) play a crucial role in verifying that these corrective actions are effectively implemented and compliant with regulations. The Core Module integrates concepts from established ontologies like DiCon and OCQA, enabling comprehensive representation of locations, activities, equipment, agents, and organizations. This integration allows seamless alignment with construction schedules and resource allocations, enhancing the interoperability of safety and construction knowledge. By incorporating these elements, the Core Module ensures adaptability to dynamic construction environments and supports a variety of safety management scenarios. The modular design also promotes flexibility and reuse across projects, ensuring that the ontology can evolve to meet new requirements.

Figure 1: Overview of Core UNOCS module.

UNOCS - Hazard

The Hazard Representation Module is a critical part of the UNOCS ontology, designed to model and represent various hazards encountered in construction environments. At its core is the unocs:Hazard class, which provides a structured framework to represent hazards and their associated properties, ensuring alignment with safety regulations. Hazards are connected to risks (unocs:Risk) and incidents (unocs:Incident), enabling detailed representation and analysis of safety scenarios. To classify hazards as controlled or uncontrolled, the module incorporates attributes that evaluate risk levels against predefined thresholds (unocs:ResidualRisk). Controlled hazards meet specific requirements (unocs:Requirements) through corrective actions (unocs:CorrectiveAction) that transform non-conformities into conformance, as per ISO standards. The temporal and spatial aspects of hazards are inherited from dicp:Activity, allowing integration with construction schedules and defining the location, agents, and building objects involved. The module also addresses hazard categorization standards, including frameworks like the Energy Wheel, BG BAU, and PAS1192, providing interoperability across various regulatory systems. Specific subclasses, such as unocs:FallFromLadder and unocs:SlipOrTripOnSameLevel, enable detailed management of fall-related hazards. The Hazard Representation Module facilitates comprehensive hazard analysis, supports compliance with safety regulations, and improves construction safety management. Through its structured design, it provides the flexibility to adapt to diverse standards and project-specific requirements.

Figure 1: Overview of Core UNOCS module.

UNOCS - Mitigation

The Mitigation Module of UNOCS focuses on managing hazards to ensure they are controlled and their residual risks are reduced to acceptable levels. Controlled hazards meet specific requirements (unocs:Requirements) through planned corrective actions (unocs:CorrectiveAction), which eliminate non-conformities as outlined by ISO:45001 standards. This module addresses the inconsistency in terminology across construction safety by providing a unified framework that encompasses terms such as control measures, mitigation measures, and treatment plans. Corrective actions in UNOCS inherit temporal and spatial attributes from dicp:Activity, enabling integration into construction schedules. These actions specify start and end dates, locations, and assigned workers (unocs:Agent) responsible for execution. Additionally, corrective actions involve building objects (e.g., fall protection systems, hole covers) and equipment (e.g., hard hats, sun protection), which are essential for mitigating hazards effectively. The aggregation of all corrective actions forms the unocs:MitigationPlan, which represents a comprehensive set of activities designed to address known hazards on a construction site. This plan ensures that all safety measures are implemented and validated through inspection processes, providing a structured approach to hazard mitigation. By unifying mitigation concepts and integrating them with existing safety standards, the Mitigation Module enhances the ability to manage safety risks systematically and adapt to diverse construction scenarios.

Figure 1: Overview of Core UNOCS module.

UNOCS - Safety

Relevant entities for safety inspections address various aspects of inspection processes within the construction safety domain. The central entity, unocs:SafetyInspection, inherits from dicp:Activity to incorporate the temporal aspect, required equipment, and the assignment of a responsible worker to complete the task. The purpose of the inspection is to verify the correct implementation of corrective control actions and the associated corrective control entity. Consequently, the inspection must ensure follow-up on the corrective control action.

The inspection is linked to several requirements outlined in regulations, with each requirement defining the necessary characteristics of corrective control entities. However, the actual characteristics of these entities may differ from the specified requirements. A nonconformity arises if the actual characteristics deviate from the requirements, necessitating the initiation of a new corrective action.

Figure 1: Overview of Core UNOCS module.

Actorc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Agents#Actor
Description

An agent that performs activities.

Person, organization or organizational unit involved in a construction process (ISO 19650-1, def 3.2.1).

Note 1: Organizational units include, but are not limited to, departments, teams.

Note 2: In the context of ISO 19650-1, construction processes take place during the delivery phase and the operational phase.

DeliveryTeamc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Agents#DeliveryTeam
Description

Lead appointed party and their appointed parties (ISO 19650-1, def. 3.2.6).

Note 1: A delivery team can be any size, from one person carrying out all the necessary functions through to complex, multi-layered task teams. The size and structure of each delivery team are in response to the scale and complexity of the asset management or project delivery activities.

Note 2: Multiple delivery teams can be appointed simultaneously and/or sequentially in connection with a single asset or project, in response to the scale and complexity of the asset management or project delivery activities.

Note 3: A delivery team can consist of multiple task teams from within the lead appointed party’s organization and any appointed parties.

Note 4: A delivery team can be assembled by the appointing party rather than the lead appointed party. (ISO 19650-1, def. 3.2.6)
Super-classes https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Agents#Teamc
In range of https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Agents#hasProjectTeamop

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#Context
Description

An identified realm of data, representing the circumstances in which the data can be considered true. Examples are (1) intentional contexts such as a requirement definition, a plan or a design, (2) actual contexts such as actual activity execution or a model of constructed building (as-built model), or (3) a time period when a statement holds.

ContextFrameworkc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#ContextFramework
Description

Context framework is an identified collection of contexts that belong together. Examples are (1) a framework of design contexts consisting of as-is, as-designed, and as-built contexts, (2) a framework of management contexts consisting of contexts for planned and actual execution, and (3) a framework for levels of detail such as BIMForum2018 LOD model.
In domain of https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#hasContextop
In range of https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#isContextOfop

ContextSetc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#ContextSet
Description

A set of active contexts. It can include a compatible set of contexts for design information (e.g., LOD400 BIM models), organizational structures (e.g., location breakdown structure), a currenty valid master plan, compatible lookahead plan, the week plan for current week, and a context for actual execution data. The can be a unique "current ContexSet" and there can be ContextSet for different periods of time or for different renovation scenarios.
Sub-classes https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#InformationModelc
In domain of https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#hasModalContextop

Groupc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Entities#Group
Description

A set of entities. Examples are sets created for management purposes, such as a procurement package, a cost control item, a shipment, a material kit, a workgroup, or the walls of a space. One group may contain entities belonging to otherwise disjoint fundamental categories, such as material batches, equipment, information content entities, and activities.

InformationContainerc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#InformationContainer
Description

InformationContainer is a named persistent set of information (ISO 19650-1 3.3.1) retrievable from within a file, system or application storage hierarchy (ISO 19650-1 def. 3.3.12)

InformationContainer needs to be used when there is a need to represent information contents that consist of indefinite set of statements (composed of indefinite set of entities with indefinite set of mutual relations), that can create complex networks. Examples are complex designs, plans, linksets, and so on.

EXAMPLE Including sub-directory, information file (including model, document, table, schedule), or distinct sub-set of an information file such as a chapter or section, layer or symbol.

InformationModelc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#InformationModel
Description

A set of structured and unstructured information containers (ISO 19650-1, def. 3.3.8)

Asset information models (AIM) and project information models (PIM) are the structured repositories of information needed for making decisions during the whole life cycle of a built environment asset. This includes the design and construction of new assets, refurbishment of existing assets, and the operation and maintenance of an asset. It should be expected that the amount of information stored in information models, and the different purposes it will be used for, will mostly increase during project delivery and asset management. (ISO 19650-1, ch. 4.1)

AIM and PIM can include structured and unstructured information. Examples of structured information include geometrical models, schedules and databases. Examples of unstructured information include documentation, video clips and sound recordings. (ISO 19650-1, ch. 4.1)

The whole information model is not always held in one place, particularly for large or complex assets or projects, or widely dispersed teams. (ISO 19650-1, ch. 12.1)

Note: ISO 21597 ICDD ContainerDescription is aligned as a subclass of the InformationModel (based on the ISO 19650 "Information model").
Super-classes https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Contexts#ContextSetc
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#InformationContentEntityc
Sub-classes https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#ProjectInformationModelc
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#Catalogc
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#AssetInformationModelc
In domain of https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#includesModelop
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#hasContainerSetop
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#includesContainerop
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#modelIncludedInop
https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#hasDefaultContainerSetop
In range of https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#modelIncludedInop

ProjectInformationModelc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#ProjectInformationModel
Description

Project information model (PIM) is an Information model (3.3.8) relating to the delivery phase of a Built asset. (ISO 19650-1, def. 3.3.10)

Note: During the project, the project information model can be used to convey the design intent (sometimes called the design intent model) or the virtual representation of the asset to be constructed (sometimes called the virtual construction model). (ISO 19650-1, def. 3.3.10)

Project information model (PIM) is a structured repository of information needed for making decisions during the delivery stage of a Built asset. It should be expected that the amount of information stored in PIM, and the different purposes it will be used for, will mostly increase during project delivery. PIM can include structured and unstructured information. (ISO 19650-1, def. 4.1)
Super-classes https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#InformationModelc
Restrictions https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Information#isAboutop only https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Processes#Projectc

CostFeatureCatalogc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/ocqa-catalog#CostFeatureCatalog
Description

The CostFeatureCatalog is a catalog that encompasses various parameters or features related to costs in the context of quality assurance in construction execution. This can include costs for materials, equipment, man-hours, and other relevant aspects. The purpose of this catalog is to provide a structured and organized collection of cost parameters that can be used for accurate calculation and planning in construction projects.
Super-classes https://w3id.org/ocqa-catalog#FeatureCatalogc

FailureProbabilityCatalogc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/ocqa-catalog#FailureProbabilityCatalog
Description

The FailureProbabilityCatalog is a catalog containing various parameters concerning the probability of errors or failures in the quality assurance of construction execution. This might relate to the likelihood of specific materials failing or the efficiency of particular construction methods. The goal of this catalog is to better assess and minimize risks.
Super-classes https://w3id.org/ocqa-catalog#FeatureCatalogc

TimeRateCatalogc # Classes

URI https://w3id.org/ocqa-catalog#TimeRateCatalog
Description

The TimeRateCatalog is a catalog that includes parameters or features concerning time estimations in the context of quality assurance in construction execution. This can relate to the time required for various processes, such as preparation, execution, or post-processing. Through this catalog, construction projects can be better planned and optimized in terms of time.

hasUnitCostdp # DPs

URI https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Processes#hasUnitCost
Description

The unit cost of a resource. Unit cost (e.g., 10€/m2), together with the information about cost unit (here, m2) and usage amount of expressed in cost units (e.g., 32) can be used to compute the total cost (here, 320€). Or if unit cost is 50€/hr and the cost unit is hr and usage amount 12, the total cost is 600€
Domain(s) https://w3id.org/digitalconstruction/0.5/Processes#Resourcec
